        generic
        /dnrk/
        Learn to pronounce
        adjective
        adjective: generic
        1. 1.
          characteristic of or relating to a class or group of things; not specific.
          "chvre is a generic term for all goat's milk cheese"
          h
          Similar:
          general
          common
          collective
          non-specific
          inclusive
          all-inclusive
          all-encompassing
          broad
          comprehensive
          blanket
          umbrella
          sweeping
          universal
          cross-disciplinary
          interdisciplinary
          multidisciplinary
          h
          Opposite:
          specific
          • (of goods, especially medicinal drugs) having no brand name; not protected by a registered trademark.
            h
            Similar:
            unbranded
            untrademarked
            non-proprietary
            h
            Opposite:
            branded
          • derogatory
            lacking imagination or individuality; predictable and unoriginal.
            "generic dance-floor fillers"
        2. 2.
          Biology
          relating to a genus.
        noun
        noun: generic; plural noun: generics
        1. a consumer product having no brand name or registered trademark.
          "substituting generics for brand-name drugs"
        Origin
        late 17th century: from French gnrique, from Latin genus, gener- stock, race.

        Use over time for: generic

        What does it mean if something is generic?
        (Entry 1 of 2) 1a : relating to or characteristic of a whole group or class : general "Romantic comedy" is the generic term for such films. b : not being or having a particular brand name generic drugs. c : having no particularly distinctive quality or application generic restaurants.

        Generic content is unspecific content. ... This type of content does not have the impact that more specific content has, and the information is nothing a reader wouldn't have seen before. Therefore, there is no real hook to keep a reader interested in the article you have written have glanced at.

        Generic brand
        Generic brand
        Generic brands of consumer products are distinguished by the absence of a brand name, instead identified solely by product characteristics and identified by plain, usually black-and-white packaging. Generally they imitate more expensive branded products, competing on price.

        Generic drug

        Description

        Description

        A generic drug is a pharmaceutical drug that contains the same chemical substance as a drug that was originally protected by chemical patents. Generic drugs are allowed for sale after the patents on the original drugs expire. Wikipedia
